INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (700, 1, '2014-03-10 18:58:40', '2014-03-10 18:58:40', '<h2>Here\'s the story on The AGSC and Usage Rights.</h2>\n\n<p><strong>What are usage rights?</strong></p>\n\n<p>Usage rights define the scenarios within which you are allowed to distribute or display the artwork we design for you or your organisation.</p>\n\n<p><strong>What are these scenarios?</strong></p>\n\n<p>The following are the primary usage scenarios:</p>\n\n<ul><li>Presentation<ul><li>Allows distribution of the design internally. This is perfect for road testing or workshopping a design before making it public.</li></ul>\n</li><li>Social Media</li><li>Website(s)</li><li>Print Media<ul><li>I.e. brochures, flyers, business cards etc</li></ul>\n</li><li>Large Format Print Media<ul><li>I.e. billboards, vinyl banners etc</li></ul>\n</li><li>Television</li><li>Buyout<ul><li>This transfers full rights to the design to you or your organisation.</li></ul></li></ul>\n\n<p><strong>Why can\'t I just use my finished design wherever I want? I paid for it, right? Isn\'t it mine?</strong></p>\n\n<p>Very good question. There are two main reasons we charge for various usage rights. The first is so you the client aren\'t paying for rights you don\'t need. If you are setting up an online business that sells custom printed envelopes, you aren\'t likely to need rights to use the design for Television or Large Format Print Media. </p>\n\n<p><strong>Oh, so they cost money?</strong></p>\n', 'Usage Rights', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '697-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-03-10 18:58:40', '2014-03-10 18:58:40', '', 697, 'http://theagsc.com/community/697-revision-v1', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (701, 1, '2014-03-10 19:36:34', '2014-03-10 19:36:34', '<h2>Here\'s the story on The AGSC and Usage Rights.</h2>\n\n<h3>What are usage rights?  </h3>\n\n<p>Usage rights define the scenarios within which you are allowed to distribute or display the artwork we design for you or your organisation.</p>\n\n<h3>What are these scenarios?  </h3>\n\n<p>The following are the primary usage scenarios:</p>\n\n<ul><li>Presentation<ul><li>Allows distribution of the design internally. This is perfect for road testing or workshopping a design before making it public.</li></ul>\n</li><li>Social Media</li><li>Website(s)</li><li>Print Media<ul><li>I.e. brochures, flyers, business cards etc</li></ul>\n</li><li>Large Format Print Media<ul><li>I.e. billboards, vinyl banners etc</li></ul>\n</li><li>Television</li><li>Buyout<ul><li>This transfers full rights to the design to you or your organisation.</li></ul></li></ul>\n\n<h3>Why can\'t I just use my finished design wherever I want? I paid for it, right? Isn\'t it mine?  </h3>\n\n<p>As the original creator, we retain the copyright for our designs. Charging for the rights to use our work reinforces the value of the artwork, and it\'s potential to advance your brand, increase revenue, and basically make you look really good.</p>\n\n<p>Very good question. There are two main reasons we charge for various usage rights. The first is so you the client aren\'t paying for rights you don\'t need. If you are setting up an online business that sells custom printed envelopes, you aren\'t likely to need rights to use the design for Television or Large Format Print Media. </p>\n\n<h3>Oh, so they cost money?</h3>\n', 'Usage Rights', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '697-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-03-10 19:36:34', '2014-03-10 19:36:34', '', 697, 'http://theagsc.com/community/697-revision-v1', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (702, 1, '2014-03-10 20:14:40', '2014-03-10 20:14:40', '<h2>Here\'s the story on The AGSC and Usage Rights.</h2>\n\n<h3>What are usage rights?</h3>\n\n<p>Usage rights define the scenarios within which you are allowed to distribute or display the artwork we design for you or your organisation.</p>\n\n<h3>What are the scenarios?</h3>\n\n<p>The following are the primary usage scenarios:</p>\n\n<ul><li>Presentation<ul><li>Allows distribution of the design internally. This is perfect for road testing or workshopping a design before making it public.</li></ul>\n</li><li>Social Media</li><li>Website(s)</li><li>Print Media<ul><li>I.e. brochures, flyers, business cards etc</li></ul>\n</li><li>Large Format Print Media<ul><li>I.e. billboards, vinyl banners etc</li></ul>\n</li><li>Television</li><li>Buyout<ul><li>This transfers full rights to the design to you or your organisation.</li></ul></li></ul>\n\n<h3>Why can\'t I just use my finished design wherever I want? I paid for it, right? Isn\'t it mine?</h3>\n\n<p>Very good question. </p>\n\n<p>As the original creator, we retain the copyright for our designs. Charging for the rights to use our work reinforces the value of the artwork, and its\' potential to advance your brand, increase revenue, and basically make you look really good. It also preserves the artworks\' integrity, and by extension, the visual integrity of your brand, by preventing changes from being made to it.</p>\n\n<h3>You mentioned a charge; do usage rights cost money?</h3>\n\n<p>Yes, we charge for rights based on a number of factors, including the size of your business, the required usage scenarios and the type of project.</p>\n\n<p>If you are starting an online business selling custom printed greeting cards and need a logo, it is unlikely you will require Large Format Print Media or Television rights, so you can save money by only opting for the usage scenarios that make sense for you. Additionally, a international bank would be charged more for using artwork in various scenarios than the greeting card print shop. It\'s all relative, and geared towards saving you money and making the most of the designs we create for you.</p>\n\n<h3>OK, that makes sense. But what if I only need to use a design for a short period of time?</h3>\n\n<p>If you are hosting an event, conference etc, you may only require rights for a finite period of time; i.e. 4 months as you advertise, hold, and wind down from an event. This is completely fine, and when we draft up your contract we will make sure you are only paying for those months.</p>\n\n<h3>I like that sketch you created earlier on; can I have the sketches included in the projects\' final deliverables?</h3>\n\n<p>It\'s not unusual for a preliminary sketch to catch a clients eye, even after the completion of the final product. While we don\'t actually include sketches in the files we deliver, we are more than happy to chat about developing a sketch at an additional cost. Email us for more info: hello@theagsc.com</p>\n\n<h3>To heck with usage rights, I want full rights in my name.</h3>\n\n<p>This is fine too. We can arrange a buyout. A buyout grants full rights to your or your organisation. Depending on your needs, this can be for a finite period of time, or a permanent transfer of rights. A buyout is the most expensive of all the scenarios, and costing is estimated on a job-by-job basis.</p>\n', 'Usage Rights', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '697-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-03-10 20:14:40', '2014-03-10 20:14:40', '', 697, 'http://theagsc.com/community/697-revision-v1', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
