INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (945, 1, '2014-04-28 17:06:25', '2014-04-28 17:06:25', '<p>So you\'ve created your artwork—for this tutorial let\'s say a logotype—in Illustrator and warmed it up in Photoshop (or other graphics editors <sup><a href="#ref-01">[1]</a></sup>) with some subtle effects. You\'re left with a sweet looking logo, but one that is constrained to a mere bitmap. Let\'s take a look at an easy way of breathing the beziers back into your work.</p>\r\n<p>Here\'s an example, fresh from Ai:</p>\r\n<p><img src="https://www.evernote.com/shard/s71/sh/bdfe1a53-8ba9-4df0-ab98-daf663af81af/b8d63d4331bc2c3df54183735897187e/deep/0/fig01.png" alt="Fig. 01"/></p>\r\n<p><figcaption>Fig. 01</figcaption></p>\r\n<p>Here\'s the same logo, with a few effects applied (both in Ai and Ps—<em>tutorial on this effect coming soon.</em>)</p>\r\n<p><img src="https://www.evernote.com/shard/s71/sh/85d0ef33-7f5a-4772-8983-3d12ab041bd6/20fb249851a09c6511fab79783dd730c/deep/0/fig02.png" alt="Fig. 02"/></p>\r\n<p><figcaption>Fig. 02</figcaption></p>\r\n<p>To convert this logo back to vector format requires a few simple steps.</p>\r\n<h2>Make my logo bigger</h2><p>To apply those effects, you would have created a new canvas in Ps and brought in your artwork from Ai. For the first step we are going to <em>enlarge</em> that canvas. Head up to <code>Image &gt; Image Size...</code> ( <code>⌥⌘I</code>) and set the <code>Width</code> to around 8,000–10,000px (make sure you\'ve constrained the canvas\' proportions by clicking the lock icon). Sounds pretty big—and it is. If you\'re worried about superfluous file size/disk usage, you can save out a JPG at that size and keep your working file smaller. (<em>Note: if you\'re worried about losing fidelity by enlarging your artwork, there\'s a chance you\'re not making full use of smart objects and clipping masks! But it\'s OK, we are working away on a tutorial for that too—all about non-destructive/smart linked/action-based workflows. <a href="http://eepurl.com/MEK_z">Subscribe</a> to be the first to know when that\'s released; should be a good one.</em>)</p>\r\n<h2>Trace!</h2><p>You\'ve all heard of <code>Live Trace</code> (or <code>Image Trace</code> as it is now called). It can be a tool for good or for evil. For this tutorial, we\'re going to open our PSD or JPG in Ai, and use <code>Image Trace</code> to convert our raster artwork to vector once again. We blew up the size of our Ps document to give Ai the best chance of correctly representing our logo in vector form—the more pixels you give it to work with, the more accurately it interprets your image.</p>\r\n<p>Head to <code>File &gt; Open...</code> and select your PSD/JPG file. Ensure \'Flatten Layers to a Single Image\' is selected. Hit OK.</p>\r\n<p>With your artwork selected, head to <code>Window</code> and ensure the <code>Image Trace</code> tab is visible. Click on the \'Advanced\' arrow and tick \'Ignore White\'. Hit preview and check out the result.</p>\r\n<p>There\'s a good chance it\'s looking pretty good at this stage—make sure you\'re zoomed out to take it all in. If some lines have strayed a little, try unticking \'Snap Curves to Lines\' (ticked, this option replaces slightly curved lines with straight lines, reducing unnecessary nodes).</p>\r\n<p>It\'s worth having a play with the \'Threshold\' slider as well—it yields behaviour reminiscent of Fig. 16 from [Hopscotch Tutorial link].</p>\r\n<h2>Expand</h2><p>Once you\'re happy with how it\'s looking, commit the results by hitting <code>Expand</code>.</p>\r\n<p>That\'s it! Save that as an Ai file with the rest of your project, and you now have a perfectly scalable vector version of your raster-edited logotype. </p>\r\n<h3>References</h3><p><div id="ref-01" class="ref"><sup> <code>[1]</code> </sup>Let\'s not forget there are a bunch of alternatives out there; <a href="http://www.inkscape.org/en/">Inkscape</a>, <a href="http://bohemiancoding.com/sketch/">Sketch</a>, <a href="http://www.gimp.org/">GIMP</a> etc. Let us know if and what you prefer about these editors over Adobe products.</div></p>\r\n', 'Quick Tip #01: Returning Your Artwork to Vector After Editing in Photoshop', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '918-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-04-28 17:06:25', '2014-04-28 17:06:25', '', 918, 'http://theagsc.com/community/918-revision-v1', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
