INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (951, 1, '2014-04-28 18:13:05', '2014-04-28 18:13:05', '<p>So you\'ve created your artwork—for this tutorial let\'s say a logotype—in <span class="ai">Ai</span> and warmed it up in <span class="ps">Ps</span> (or other graphics editors <sup><a href="#ref-01">[1]</a></sup>) with some subtle effects. You\'re left with a sweet looking logo, but one that is constrained to a mere bitmap. Let\'s take a look at an easy way of breathing the beziers back into your work.</p>\r\n<p>Here\'s an example, fresh from Ai:</p>\r\n<p><img src="https://www.evernote.com/shard/s71/sh/bdfe1a53-8ba9-4df0-ab98-daf663af81af/b8d63d4331bc2c3df54183735897187e/deep/0/fig01.png" alt="Fig. 01"/></p>\r\n<p><figcaption>Fig. 01</figcaption></p>\r\n<p>Here\'s the same logo, with a few effects applied (both in <span class="ai">Ai</span> and <span class="ps">Ps</span>—<em>tutorial on this effect coming soon.</em>)</p>\r\n<p><img src="https://www.evernote.com/shard/s71/sh/85d0ef33-7f5a-4772-8983-3d12ab041bd6/20fb249851a09c6511fab79783dd730c/deep/0/fig02.png" alt="Fig. 02"/></p>\r\n<p><figcaption>Fig. 02</figcaption></p>\r\n<p>To convert this logo back to vector format requires a few simple steps.</p>\r\n<h2>Make my logo bigger</h2><p>To apply those effects, you would have created a new canvas in <span class="ps">Ps</span> and brought in your artwork from <span class="ai">Ai</span>. For the first step we are going to <em>enlarge</em> that canvas. Head up to <code>Image &gt; Image Size...</code> ( <code>⌥⌘I</code>) and set the width to around <code>8,000</code> – <code>10,000px</code> (make sure you\'ve constrained the canvas\' proportions by clicking the lock icon). Sounds pretty big—and it is. If you\'re worried about superfluous file size/disk usage, you can save out a <code>*.jpg</code> at that size and keep your working file smaller. (<em>Note: If you find you\'re losing fidelity by enlarging your artwork, there\'s a good chance you\'re not making full use of Smart Objects and Clipping Masks! We are working away on a tutorial on that too—all about non-destructive, smart-linked, action-based workflows. <a href="http://eepurl.com/MEK_z">Subscribe</a> to be among the first to know when that\'s released.</em>)</p>\r\n<h2>Trace!</h2><p>You\'ve all heard of <em>Live Trace</em> (or <em>Image Trace</em> as it is now called). It can be a tool for good or for evil. For this tutorial, we\'re going to open our <code>*.psd</code> or <code>*.jpg</code> in <span class="ai">Ai</span>, and use <em>Image Trace</em> to convert our raster artwork to vector once again. We blew up the size of our <span class="ps">Ps</span> document to give <span class="ai">Ai</span> the best chance of correctly interpolating our logo in vector form—the more pixels you give it to work with, the more accurately it interprets your image.</p>\r\n<p>Head to <code>File &gt; Open...</code> and select your <code>*.psd</code> / <code>*.jpg</code> file. Ensure <em>Flatten Layers to a Single Image</em> is selected. Hit <em>OK</em>.</p>\r\n<p>With your artwork selected, head to <code>Window</code> and ensure the <code>Image Trace</code> tab is visible. Click on the <em>Advanced</em> arrow and tick <em>Ignore White</em>. Hit <em>Preview</em> and check out the result.</p>\r\n<p>There\'s a good chance it\'s looking great at this stage—make sure you\'re zoomed out to take it all in. If some lines have strayed a little, try unticking <em>Snap Curves to Lines</em> (ticked, this option replaces slightly curved lines with straight lines, reducing unnecessary nodes).</p>\r\n<p>It\'s worth having a play with the <em>Threshold</em> slider as well—it yields behaviour reminiscent of <em>Fig. 16</em> from <a href="http://dev.theagsc.com//community/tutorials/creating-a-hand-lettered-logotype-from-beginning-to-end," title="Creating">our tutorial on creating a logotype from beginning to end</a>.</p>\r\n<h2>Expand</h2><p>Once you\'re happy with how it\'s looking, commit the results by hitting <code>Expand</code>.</p>\r\n<p>That\'s it! Save that as an Ai file with the rest of your project, and you now have a perfectly scalable vector version of your raster-edited logotype. </p>\r\n<h3>References</h3><p><div id="ref-01" class="ref"><sup> <code>[1]</code> </sup>Let\'s not forget there are a bunch of alternatives out there; <a href="http://www.inkscape.org/en/">Inkscape</a>, <a href="http://bohemiancoding.com/sketch/">Sketch</a>, <a href="http://www.gimp.org/">GIMP</a> etc. Let us know if and what you prefer about these editors over Adobe products.</div></p>\r\n', 'Quick Tip #01: Returning Your Artwork to Vector After Editing in Photoshop', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '918-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-04-28 18:13:05', '2014-04-28 18:13:05', '', 918, 'http://theagsc.com/community/918-revision-v1', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
