des).</p>\r\n<p>It\'s worth having a play with the <em>Threshold</em> slider as well—it yields behaviour reminiscent of <em>Fig. 16</em> from <a href="http://dev.theagsc.com//community/tutorials/creating-a-hand-lettered-logotype-from-beginning-to-end" title=" Visit &apos;Creating a Hand Lettered Logotype from Beginning to End&apos;">our tutorial on creating a logotype from beginning to end</a>.</p>\r\n<h2>Expand</h2><p>Once you\'re happy with how it\'s looking, commit the results by hitting <code>Expand</code>.</p>\r\n<p>That\'s it! Save that as an <code>*.ai</code> file with the rest of your project, and you now have a perfectly scalable vector version of your raster-edited logotype. Here\'s a side-by-side comparison of the vector vs. bitmap versions:</p>\r\n<p><img src="https://www.evernote.com/shard/s71/sh/bd801f63-59cf-4a2f-977e-eb7b0ee65d08/71598f791dab2f71055bcd9fbee4864b/deep/0/fig04.png" alt="Fig. 04"/></p>\r\n<p><figcaption>Fig. 04 – Vector on the left, bitmap on the right. Vector ends up being slightly more crunchy.</figcaption></p>\r\n<p>In enlarging our canvas sufficiently, <em>Image Trace</em> has had plenty of material to work with, and has produced an acceptable vector equivalent. </p>\r\n<h2>A summary (and some very <s>boring</s> nerdy stats)</h2><p>There are a few wee things to consider when going back to vector. One is that the final vector file produced shouldn\'t be used to edit or tweak the logo. <em>Always</em> make your edits in the original <code>*.ai</code> (i.e. <em>Fig. 01</em>) and update your files down the line until you get back to a new, updated, final vector file. As we mentioned before, we are currently working on a new tutorial that goes in-depth on how to make this process sing.</p>\r\n<p>Another thing is that the resulting vector file will be larger and more bloated with nodes than your original logotype. For some perspective, our original file for the \'Trace\' artwork is made up of 67 nodes, and sits at 142Kb; a fairly modest figure. Once edited in <span class="ps">Ps</span> and re-vectorised, however, it weighed in at a ungainly 2806 points and 222Kb. To be fair, this difference is all but completely unnoticeable, but if you do feel led to go through and give some love to your final file, the hard working folks over at <a href="http://www.astutegraphics.com/" title="ai">Astute Graphics</a> have got some very powerful plugins for <span class="ai">Ai</span>, such as <a href="http://www.astutegraphics.com/software/vectorscribe/">VectorScribe</a>, which offers (among a myriad of other fantastic tools) a <code>Smart Remove Brush Tool</code>, that automatically finds and removes unnecessary points along your vector paths.</p>\r\n<h3>References</h3><p><div id="ref-01" class="ref"><sup> <code>[1]</code> </sup>Let\'s not forget there are a bunch of alternatives out there; <a href="http://www.inkscape.org/en/">Inkscape</a>, <a href="http://bohemiancoding.com/sketch/">Sketch</a>, <a href="http://www.gimp.org/">GIMP</a> etc. Let us know if and what you prefer about these editors over Adobe products.</div></p>\r\n', 'Quick Tip #01: Returning Your Artwork to Vector After Editing in Photoshop', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '918-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-04-28 19:41:22', '2014-04-28 19:41:22', '', 918, 'http://theagsc.com/community/918-revision-v1', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
